Evaluation Phase (The Answer Key)
Once you've attempted the tasks, use this key to grade yourself. Each task is worth 10 points. You need a 70 to pass.

Task 1: System Reconnaissance (10 Points)

Bash

hostname > /root/system_info.txt
(You could also use hostnamectl or cat /etc/hostname)

Task 2: The Directory Tree (10 Points)

Bash

mkdir -p /opt/training/linux101
touch /opt/training/linux101/practice.txt
(The -p flag in mkdir is required to create parent directories that don't exist yet!)

Task 3: Basic User Management (10 Points)

Bash

useradd intern1
passwd intern1 
# (Then type the password twice when prompted)
Task 4: Group Assignment (10 Points)

Bash

groupadd juniors
usermod -aG juniors intern1
(Forgetting the -a flag here is the most common beginner mistake!)

Task 5: Ownership and Permissions (10 Points)

Bash

chgrp juniors /opt/training/linux101
chmod 770 /opt/training/linux101
(You can also use chmod ug+rwx,o-rwx /opt/training/linux101)

Task 6: Text Manipulation (10 Points)

Bash

echo "I am learning Red Hat" >> /opt/training/linux101/practice.txt
(You must use >> to append. If you used >, it would overwrite the file—which is fine here since it was empty, but >> is safer!)

Task 7: Searching for Text (10 Points)

Bash

grep "ssh" /etc/services > /root/ssh_port.txt
Task 8: Archiving and Compression (10 Points)

Bash

tar -czvf /root/training_backup.tar.gz /opt/training
(Flags: c=create, z=gzip, v=verbose/show output, f=file)

Task 9: Package Management (10 Points)

Bash

dnf install tmux -y
Task 10: Basic Service Management (10 Points)

Bash

systemctl status sshd
systemctl enable sshd
(You can also combine them with systemctl enable --now sshd if it wasn't running).
